    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with a high-ceiling core anchored by **James Wood**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Mickey Moniak**, all of whom cleared the 75-point threshold. **James Wood** is our premier play today, benefiting from a high-leverage leadoff spot and a favorable matchup against McGreevy. Meanwhile, **Mickey Moniak** and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** are positioned to capitalize on significant platoon and park factor boosts. **Trevor Story** warrants a mention as a high-value utility play, as his projection spiked to 71.18 due to a premium matchup against Drohan\u2019s shaky 10.13 xERA, allowing him to outperform several regular starters despite his mid-order slotting.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Austin Riley** on the bench. Despite a respectable score of 44.64, the combination of a tough matchup against Detmers and a lack of elite speed compared to our outfield-heavy lineup made him the odd man out; he remains a high-floor asset, but the optimizer favored the platoon advantages currently enjoyed by **Tyler Soderstrom** and **Corbin Carroll**. We are also keeping a close eye on **Corbin Carroll**, whose 64.19 score is slightly suppressed by a negative park adjustment; however, his elite 0.372 xwOBA remains a cornerstone of our offensive production.\n\nRisks today are concentrated in the infield, specifically regarding **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **Max Muncy**. **Vinnie Pasquantino** faces a harsh 15% penalty due to a negative platoon split against the lefty Cantillo, resulting in a marginal 48.67 score. We are also monitoring the volatility of the bottom-third of our order; while **Kyle Karros** benefits from a massive 14% park boost, his status as the #9 hitter limits his counting stat potential. Ensure all game caps are monitored closely, as players like **Austin Riley** and **Alex Freeland** are ready to rotate in should any of our primary starters face defensive substitutions or mid-game rest.",
